ğŸ› ï¸ Explanation of Each Part
; ğŸ”¹ 1. venv/ (Virtual Environment)

This is a self-contained Python environment.

Each project has its own venv â†’ prevents conflicts (e.g., one project uses Django 4, another uses Django 5).

Activate it before working:

source venv/bin/activate

; ğŸ”¹ 2. manage.py

Command-line tool to interact with your project.

Examples:

python manage.py runserver â†’ starts the server

python manage.py startapp myapp â†’ create a new app

python manage.py makemigrations / migrate â†’ database handling

Always run commands from the folder containing manage.py.

; ğŸ”¹ 3. first/ (Project Folder)

This is created when you run django-admin startproject first ..
It holds project-level configuration:

__init__.py â†’ makes it a Python package.

settings.py â†’ project settings (apps, database, debug, static files).

urls.py â†’ project-wide URL routes.

asgi.py / wsgi.py â†’ entry points for web servers (deployment).

Think of this as the control center of your Django project.

; ğŸ”¹ 4. myapp/ (App Folder)

This is created with python manage.py startapp myapp.
It holds your application logic:

views.py â†’ functions/classes that handle requests and return responses.

urls.py â†’ app-level URL patterns (must be linked in project urls.py).

models.py â†’ database models (tables).

admin.py â†’ register models for Django Admin.

apps.py â†’ app configuration.

tests.py â†’ write unit tests.

migrations/ â†’ files to apply database schema changes.

You can have many apps inside one project (e.g., blog, shop, accounts).

âš™ï¸ How Django Works (Request Flow)

When you open a browser and go to http://127.0.0.1:8000/:

Browser sends request â†’ Django server receives it (runserver).

manage.py ensures Django runs using your settings.

urls.py (project level) decides which app should handle the request.

urls.py (app level) maps the request to the correct view.

views.py runs your Python function/class.

The view may:

Return simple text (HttpResponse)

Render an HTML template

Query a database (via models.py)

Response sent back â†’ Browser shows result.

ğŸ“Œ Example: Your "Hello, Sanuj!" Project

Browser: http://127.0.0.1:8000/

Project urls.py:

path('', include('myapp.urls'))


App urls.py:

path('', views.show_name)


App views.py:

return HttpResponse("Hello, Sanuj!")


Browser output:

Hello, Sanuj!


âœ… So in short:

Project folder (first/) = global settings

App folder (myapp/) = your features (views, models, templates)

manage.py = control panel

venv = isolated Python/Django environment